The '''Wine Institute''' and '''Vine Institute''' are two related organizations based in [[Athens]], [[Greece]], under the aegis of the country's [[Minister for Agriculture (Greece)|Ministry of Agriculture]]. They are devoted to researching [[Greek wine]] and to preserving and improving the country's winemaking.<ref name=lazarakis>{{cite book | author = Konstantinos Lazarakis | title = The Wines of Greece | year = 2005 | publisher = Sterling Publishing Company | isbn = 1-84000-897-0 | pages = 35–36, 40–41}}</ref>
The Wine Institute was founded in 1937, but was largely inactive until the 1960s, when it was involved in writing the first drafts of Greece's wine legislation. Since then, the Wine Institute has been primarily concerned with identifying and preserving indigenous [[List of grape varieties|grape varieties]] and [[yeast in winemaking|strains of yeast]], particularly rare ones. The Vine Institute has focused on studying the effects of different promising combinations of vines and [[terroir]], in order to provide a resource of information for Greek winemakers.<ref name=lazarakis />
